Test of the multiquark structure of a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) in strong two-body decays

Abstract

We present an analysis of strong two-body decays of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) with JP​C=1++superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶superscript1absentJ^{PC}=1^{++} recently reported by the COMPASS Collaboration at CERN. Following the interpretation of the COMPASS Collaboration that the a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} is an unusual state with a four-quark q​q¯​s​s¯𝑞¯𝑞𝑠¯𝑠q\bar{q}s\bar{s} structure we consider two possible configurations for this state — hadronic molecular and color diquark-antidiquark structures. We find that the dominant decay mode of the a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} is the decay into K𝐾K and K∗superscript𝐾K^{*}. In particular, we calculate that the four decay modes a1→V​P→subscript𝑎1𝑉𝑃a_{1}\to VP with V​P=K∗±​K∓𝑉𝑃superscript𝐾absentplus-or-minussuperscript𝐾minus-or-plusVP=K^{*\pm}K^{\mp}, K∗0​K¯0superscript𝐾absent0superscript¯𝐾0K^{*0}\bar{K}^{0}, K¯∗0​K0superscript¯𝐾absent0superscript𝐾0\bar{K}^{*0}K^{0} together give a dominant contribution to the measured total width of about 150 MeV. The observational mode a1→f0​(980)+π0→subscript𝑎1subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0a_{1}\to f_{0}(980)+\pi^{0} is significantly suppressed by one order of magnitude.

I   Introduction

Recently the COMPASS Collaboration at CERN reported Adolph:2015pws on the observation of the new state a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) with quantum numbers JP​C=1++superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶superscript1absentJ^{PC}=1^{++}. With a mass of 1414−13+15subscriptsuperscript141415131414^{+15}_{-13} MeV and a width of 153−23+8subscriptsuperscript153823153^{+8}_{-23} MeV this unusual state was interpreted by the collaboration as a tetraquark bound state with the quark content q​s​q¯​s¯𝑞𝑠¯𝑞¯𝑠qs\bar{q}\bar{s} (q=u𝑞𝑢q=u or d𝑑d). The a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) was observed in the f0​(980)​π0subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0f_{0}(980)\pi^{0} decay channel, hinting towards the large s​s¯𝑠¯𝑠s\bar{s} component.

In Ref. Gutsche:2017oro some of us applied holographic QCD to the study of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) state. In this analysis we confirmed its four-quark structure and predicted a mass of about Ma1=2subscript𝑀subscript𝑎12M_{a_{1}}=\sqrt{2} GeV ≃1.414similar-to-or-equalsabsent1.414\simeq 1.414 GeV which is in good agreement with the COMPASS result. The properties and possible structure interpretations of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) state have also been investigated in Wang:2014bua ; Chen:2015fwa using QCD sum rules and phenomenological approaches Ketzer:2015tqa -Wang:2015cis . In particular, the results of the QCD sum rule analysis of Ref. Wang:2014bua showed that the axial-vector tetraquark assignment to the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) is disfavored. Instead, the author argues that the axial-vector a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) is a mixed state of the a1​(1260)subscript𝑎11260a_{1}(1260) meson and a tetraquark state with the configuration [s​u]S=1​[s¯​d¯]S=0+[s​u]S=0​[s¯​d¯]S=1subscriptdelimited-[]𝑠𝑢𝑆1subscriptdelimited-[]¯𝑠¯𝑑𝑆0subscriptdelimited-[]𝑠𝑢𝑆0subscriptdelimited-[]¯𝑠¯𝑑𝑆1[su]_{S=1}[\bar{s}\bar{d}]_{S=0}+[su]_{S=0}[\bar{s}\bar{d}]_{S=1}. Quite differently the QCD sum rule analysis performed in Ref. Chen:2015fwa confirmed the existence of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) as a tetraquark state. Questions related to the nature of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) meson have also been addressed in other papers. In particular, it has been proposed that this state is a consequence of rescattering effects, and in fact in Ref. Ketzer:2015tqa the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) was interpreted as a dynamical effect due to a singularity (branch point) in the triangle diagram formed by the processes a1​(1260)→K∗​K¯→subscript𝑎11260superscript𝐾¯𝐾a_{1}(1260)\to K^{*}\bar{K}, K∗→K​π→superscript𝐾𝐾𝜋K^{*}\to K\pi and K​K¯→f0​(980)→𝐾¯𝐾subscript𝑓0980K\bar{K}\to f_{0}(980). In Ref. Basdevant:2015wma it was shown that a single I=1𝐼1I=1 spin-parity JP​C=1++superscript𝐽𝑃𝐶superscript1absentJ^{PC}=1^{++} a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} resonance can manifest itself as two separated mass peaks. One mass peak decays into an S𝑆S-wave ρ​π𝜌𝜋\rho\pi final state and the second one decays into a P𝑃P-wave f0​(980)​πsubscript𝑓0980𝜋f_{0}(980)\pi system, hence the tetraquark interpretation remains unclear. In Ref. Liu:2015taa it was claimed that a resonance such as the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) could be produced because of an “anomalous triangle singularity”, if the resonance is located in a specific kinematical region. In Ref. Aceti:2016yeb the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) state was considered to be a peak in the a1​(1260)→π​f0​(980)→subscript𝑎11260𝜋subscript𝑓0980a_{1}(1260)\to\pi f_{0}(980) decay mode. Finally, in Ref. Wang:2015cis it was proposed to test the possible rescattering nature of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) in heavy meson decays.

In this paper we test the four-quark structure interpretation of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) state in the study of its strong two-body decays a1​(1420)→f0​(980)+π→subscript𝑎11420subscript𝑓0980𝜋a_{1}(1420)\to f_{0}(980)+\pi and a1​(1420)→K∗+K→subscript𝑎11420superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}(1420)\to K^{*}+K using the covariant confined quark model (CCQM) proposed in Refs. Branz:2009cd ; Dubnicka:2010kz ; Dubnicka:2011mm . The CCQM has been successfully applied to the description of the properties of the exotic X​(3872)𝑋3872X(3872), Zc​(3900)subscript𝑍𝑐3900Z_{c}(3900), Z​(4430)𝑍4430Z(4430), X​(5568)𝑋5568X(5568), Zb​(10610)subscript𝑍𝑏10610Z_{b}(10610), Zb′​(10650)superscriptsubscript𝑍𝑏′10650Z_{b}^{\prime}(10650) states Dubnicka:2010kz ; Dubnicka:2011mm ; Gutsche:2016cml ; Goerke:2016hxf ; Goerke:2017svb . Our approach is based on the use of the compositeness condition Weinberg:1962hj -Efimov:1993ei originally formulated in terms of hadronic Weinberg:1962hj ; Hayashi:1967hj and later on in terms of quark constituents Efimov:1993ei . This procedure provides an opportunity to analyze both tetraquark (color diquark-antidiquark) and hadronic molecular configurations of the four constituent quarks forming the exotic state. In Refs. Goerke:2016hxf ; Goerke:2017svb we have shown that the four-quark picture with molecular-type interpolating currents are favored for the Zc​(3900)subscript𝑍𝑐3900Z_{c}(3900), Zb​(10610)subscript𝑍𝑏10610Z_{b}(10610) and Zb′​(10650)superscriptsubscript𝑍𝑏′10650Z_{b}^{\prime}(10650) states. In the case of the Zb​(10610)subscript𝑍𝑏10610Z_{b}(10610) and Zb′​(10650)superscriptsubscript𝑍𝑏′10650Z_{b}^{\prime}(10650) states there is strong experimental confirmation Garmash:2015rfd and theoretical Bondar:2011ev justification that these exotic states are four-quark states with molecular-type interpolating currents. In particular, since the masses of the Zb+​(10610)subscriptsuperscript𝑍𝑏10610Z^{+}_{b}(10610) and Zb′​(10650)superscriptsubscript𝑍𝑏′10650Z_{b}^{\prime}(10650) resonances are very close to the respective B∗​B¯superscript𝐵¯𝐵B^{*}\bar{B} (10604 MeV) and B∗​B¯∗superscript𝐵superscript¯𝐵B^{*}\bar{B}^{*} (10649 MeV) thresholds, in Ref. Bondar:2011ev it was also suggested that they have molecular-type binding structures.

We observe a similar manifestation of the hadronic molecular picture in the case of the a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} state. We find that the dominant decay modes of the a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} are the K​K⋆𝐾superscript𝐾⋆KK^{\star} channels and that the hadronic molecular configuration is preferred when compared to the color-diquark-antidiquark structure interpretation. In particular, we estimate that the four decay modes a1→V​P→subscript𝑎1𝑉𝑃a_{1}\to VP with V​P=K∗±​K∓𝑉𝑃superscript𝐾absentplus-or-minussuperscript𝐾minus-or-plusVP=K^{*\pm}K^{\mp}, K∗0​K¯0superscript𝐾absent0superscript¯𝐾0K^{*0}\bar{K}^{0}, K¯∗0​K0superscript¯𝐾absent0superscript𝐾0\bar{K}^{*0}K^{0} together nearly make up the total width of the a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} of about 150 MeV. The decay mode a1→f0​(980)+π0→subscript𝑎1subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0a_{1}\to f_{0}(980)+\pi^{0}, observed by the COMPASS Collaboration, is significantly suppressed by one order of magnitude.

The paper is organized as follows. In Sec. II, we discuss the basic notions of our approach for the description of the composite structure of mesons and tetraquark states: the choice of interpolating quark-antiquark and four-quark currents with the quantum numbers of the respective states, the Lagrangians that describe the coupling of the bound states with their constituents, and the choice of parameters. We give model independent formulas for the matrix elements and decay rates of the strong two-body decays of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420). In Sec. III we calculate matrix elements and decays rates in the framework of our covariant quark model. In Sec. IV we discuss the numerical results obtained in our approach and compare them with available experimental data. Finally, in Sec. V we summarize our findings.

II   Formalism

Next we look at the results for the a1→K∗+K→subscript𝑎1superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}\to K^{*}+K decays. Even without doing an explicit calculation it is clear that the rate for the color diquark-antidiquark configuration should be suppressed in comparison with the hadronic molecular configuration. This expectation is supported by our experience in the study of decay properties of the heavy four-quark states Zcsubscript𝑍𝑐Z_{c} and Zbsubscript𝑍𝑏Z_{b} Goerke:2016hxf ; Goerke:2017svb . Our calculations for the a1→K∗+K→subscript𝑎1superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}\to K^{*}+K decay rate also confirm this expectation. The rates in the color diquark-antidiquark scenario are suppressed by one order of magnitude in comparison with the hadronic molecular scenario. We found that results for the partial a1→K¯∗​K→subscript𝑎1superscript¯𝐾𝐾a_{1}\to\bar{K}^{*}K decay rates are very sensitive to a choice of the size parameter Λa1subscriptΛsubscript𝑎1\Lambda_{a_{1}} and decrease when the size parameter increases. Second, the results for the HM interpretation for a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) are overestimated in the region of Λa1subscriptΛsubscript𝑎1\Lambda_{a_{1}} from 0.5 to 1.5 GeV. For convenience, we show our numerical results in the two regions — from 0.5 to 1.5 GeV and 1.5 to 1.6 GeV. We present the results for four partial decay modes and for the sum of these four modes (last column). If the same value of Λa1subscriptΛsubscript𝑎1\Lambda_{a_{1}} is used in the evaluation of the decays a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) into f0​(980)​π0subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0f_{0}(980)\pi^{0} and K∗​Ksuperscript𝐾𝐾K^{*}K, the a1​(1420)→f0​(980)+π0→subscript𝑎11420subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0a_{1}(1420)\to f_{0}(980)+\pi^{0} decay width is suppressed in comparison with the a1​(1420)→K∗+K→subscript𝑎11420superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}(1420)\to K^{*}+K mode by one order of magnitude.

Finally, we would like to discuss how the obtained results may be used for interpretation of the observed a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) meson which is supposed to be q​s​q¯​s¯𝑞𝑠¯𝑞¯𝑠qs\bar{q}\bar{s} state. As was pointed out in the review Nielsen:2009uh there is no one to one correspondence between the current and the state since the CD current can be rewritten in terms of a sum over molecular type currents through the Fierz transformation. However, they have shown that the molecular components appear with the color and Dirac suppression factors. This means that if the physical state is a molecular state, it would be best to choose the HM current, and vice versa, for a tetraquark state it would be better to choose a tetraquark current. In some sense we follow this strategy. We are using both the HM and CD currents to evaluate the observed decay widths. Then we simply choose the current which is more suitable from the point of view of the experimental data.

V   Summary

We have tested the possible four-quark configuration of the a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) state by studying its strong two-body decay rates for the modes a1​(1420)→f0​(980)+π0→subscript𝑎11420subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0a_{1}(1420)\to f_{0}(980)+\pi^{0} and a1​(1420)→K∗+K→subscript𝑎11420superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}(1420)\to K^{*}+K. For both four-quark states a1​(1420)subscript𝑎11420a_{1}(1420) and f0​(980)subscript𝑓0980f_{0}(980) we have considered two possible structure scenarios — the hadronic molecular and the color diquark-antidiquark current structure. We have found that the a1​(1420)→f0​(980)+π0→subscript𝑎11420subscript𝑓0980superscript𝜋0a_{1}(1420)\to f_{0}(980)+\pi^{0} decay width is significantly suppressed in comparison to the a1​(1420)→K∗+K→subscript𝑎11420superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}(1420)\to K^{*}+K mode by one order of magnitude. Studying the decay a1​(1420)→K∗+K→subscript𝑎11420superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}(1420)\to K^{*}+K and using data of the COMPASS Collaboration Adolph:2015pws we have shown that the hadronic molecular configuration is preferred when compared to the compact colored diquark-antidiquark state. In particular, for values of the size parameter Λa1=1.56−1.58subscriptΛsubscript𝑎11.561.58\Lambda_{a_{1}}=1.56-1.58 GeV we are able to describe the available data for the total decay width of the a1subscript𝑎1a_{1} state in terms of the decay modes a1​(1420)→K∗+K→subscript𝑎11420superscript𝐾𝐾a_{1}(1420)\to K^{*}+K alone: Γsum​(a1→K∗+K)=144.70−153.44subscriptΓsum→subscript𝑎1superscript𝐾𝐾144.70153.44\Gamma_{\rm sum}(a_{1}\to K^{*}+K)=144.70-153.44 MeV.
